Entangled with Numbers: Quantified Self  
and Others in a Team-Based Online Game

YUBO KOU, Florida State University, USA 
XINNING GUI, University of California, Irvine, USA

Quantification is a process that produces and communicates numbers, imbued with the expectation of 
generating knowledge and optimizing human behavior and social process.

In this paper, we explore how 
quantification mediates virtual teamwork through an ethnographic study of quantification in League of 
Legends, a popular team-based online game with a highly competitive culture.

In the game, rich statistics 
about each individual player’s gaming history and performance are publicly available, analyzed and 
displayed on numerous third-party sites.
We describe how players were entangled with numbers.

They 
derived knowledge from numbers but struggled with proper ways of interpretation.

They utilized numbers 
to quantify teammates and opponents, but in-game tensions and conflicts easily ensued.

They noticed how 
quantification became burdensome and stressed the importance of proper use.

We discuss how this case of 
quantified self and others manifests complex relationships between self-knowledge, numerical authority, 
and virtual teamwork.1

1 INTRODUCTION

Different from collocated collaboration, in virtual teams, geographically distributed team 
members often face social challenges developing mutual trust and shared understanding [60].

Computer-supported cooperative work (CSCW) research has explored ways of conceptualizing 
and designing to support critical social elements in virtual collaboration, such as awareness [20] 
and social translucence [24].

As a way of enhancing social awareness, considerable work has 
discussed how means of representation such as a virtual profile might facilitate virtual 
collaboration [20,32,68].

Joining this stream of research, this paper analyzes how numerical 
representations of people, produced via quantification, impact virtual teamwork.

Quantification 
in this paper refers to the general social phenomenon of producing and communicating numbers 
[26].

Quantification has become a prevalent practice, as increasingly more computing systems are
made available to generate and analyze numbers about many aspects of a person’s work and life.

Famously, the Quantified Self movement denotes a trend to use technology to acquire data about 
manifold aspects of people’s daily life.

The movement, manifested in the self-tracking of health-
related aspects such as eating [13] and footsteps [31], has received lots of attention from HCI and 
CSCW researchers.

Other studies have examined academic scholars’ self-quantification through 
numbers of publications and citations [33,34,36].

However, quantification has been examined 
primarily as individuals’ acts with a focus on developing self-knowledge.

Little attention has been 
paid to how quantification structures the relationship between people and numbers in virtual 
teams.
We study quantification in virtual teams in League of Legends (LoL), currently one of the most

popular multiplayer online games in the world with more than 100 million monthly active 
players [76].

LoL’s API supports numerous third-party websites to obtain rich data about and 
establish profiles for every single player.

Players can use these quantification tools to closely 
monitor their own as well as their teammates’ numerous gameplay aspects such as gaming 
history and in-game performance.

Drawing from an ethnographic study including participant 
observation, collection and analysis of player online discussion, and semi-structured interviews, 
we describe how players quantified themselves and others in the context of virtual teamwork.

Quantification has become an integral gameplay component as players ascribed authority to 
performance-based numbers and constantly performed evaluations of self and others.

However, 
the interpretation of numbers was inherently flexible, relying heavily upon players’ situated 
knowledge of the game and the community.

Quantification also intensified virtual teamwork as 
players frequently quantified and passed judgments on others, including teammates and 
opponents.

Players also experienced stress and anxiety associated with their perceived misuse of 
quantification.

Based on these findings we discuss the complex relationship between 
quantification, self-knowledge, and virtual teamwork.
Our contributions to the CSCW literature are three-fold: First, we deepen the understanding of

quantification by describing a highly developed culture of quantification in a community where 
all the members’ data has been public available, calculated, and analyzed across multiple years; 
Second, we contribute to studies of virtual teams by discussing the use of quantification in virtual 
teamwork; Third, we analyze how quantification mediates collaborative play in online gaming.
2 BACKGROUND

League of Legends (LoL) is a multiplayer online battle arena (MOBA) game developed by Riot 
Games located in Santa Monica, California, United States.

It is currently one of the most played 
games in the world with reportedly 100 million monthly players around the world [64].

Its 
annual eSports World Championship hosted by Riot Games attracted 60 million people in 2017 
[50].
LoL’s core gameplay style is to arrange a five-versus-five match.
Prior to the start of a match,

each team of five players would first enter the “Champion Select Lobby,” where they meet each 
other for the first time, discuss later gameplay strategies, and select a champion out of more than 
130 available champions in LoL.
A typical match lasts between 20 minutes to 50 minutes.

Two 
teams are generated from a large pool of available players based on their skill, measured by

matchmaking rating (MMR), so as to create a balanced match2.

Given the massive player base, 
players assembled into a team rarely know their teammates, and must cooperate with the other 
four strangers within a short time.

An exception is that a player can “duo” with one friend, but 
the rest three teammates are strangers.

Previous work on LoL has found that these pickup groups, 
or temporary teams, face enormous challenges in creating smooth cooperation, and conflicts and 
tensions could easily erupt [43,48,71].
While MMR is what Riot Games considers as the true skill rating of a player, it is not visible to
players.
LoL has two game modes: normal and ranked.

In this paper, we focus on players 
practices related to the ranked mode.

Only in the ranked mode does LoL use a league system to 
rank and represent players’ skill level.
This skill representation is visible to players.

The league 
system consists of seven leagues, including Bronze (22.06% of all the players), Silver (49.54%), 
Gold (19.69%), Platinum (7.18%), Diamond (1.43%), Master (0.05%), and Challenger (0.02%)3.

Each 
of the first five leagues also contains five divisions, each of which has 100 league points (LP).
Players accumulate or lose LP by winning or losing matches.

Upon reaching 100 LP in a division, 
the player enters a promotion series of several matches that determines whether the player can 
be promoted to the next division.
Players can be demoted to a lower division if they reach 0 LP.
Through the past few years, the LoL game client had intermittent support for the display of
player performance-based data.

In Patch 8.15 released in July 2018, the LoL client added a new 
feature named “stats” displaying a wide range of performance-based data.

By the time of this 
study, players have relied upon third-party quantification tools that collect and analyze data from 
LoL’s API to gauge player performance.

LoL players use these tools to monitor their own 
gameplay history [46] and inform their collaboration with teammates [44].
Players can encounter discussions or recommendations of these apps in player online
communities and websites related to the game, such as LoL eSports teams’ official websites.

For 
instance, in a blog published on the website of the eSports team dignitas4, more than 80 tools 
were listed and analyzed.

The first tool, for example, is described as “Mobalytics - A personal 
performance analytics tool for League of Legends that gives detailed visualized data on all aspects 
of your play.”
Figure 1 is a screenshot of one of the most common tools (http://op.gg) that players use to
learn about their and their teammates’ performance.

As shown in Figure 1, for each single 
champion that a player has played, the statistics include the number of matched played with the 
champion, win rate of each champion, kill/death/assist ratio (KDA), average gold, average creep 
score (CS), an MMR score predicted by the tools, and so forth.

Besides the information in this 
screenshot, op.gg is highly developed with numerous tabs leading to a wealth of information 
regarding different aspects of a player’s current and past performance, such as win rate in the 
past seven days and top played champions.

__data__.text: 3.1 Knowing through Quantification

metadata.2: Knowing through Quantification

__data__.text: Quantification is a “constitutive feature of modern science and social organization” [26].

metadata.2: Knowing through Quantification

__data__.text:
It 
prevails in increasingly more aspects of our contemporary society such as manufacture, 
education, politics, economics, and health.

metadata.2: Knowing through Quantification

__data__.text:
It can also be viewed as a form of “technique” in 
Jacques Ellul’s term that is “rationally arrived at and having absolute efficiency (for a given stage 
of development) in every field of human activity” [23].

metadata.2: Knowing through Quantification

__data__.text: Particularly, self-quantification as a technique to develop knowledge about the self has been

metadata.2: Knowing through Quantification

__data__.text: often traced back to Foucault’s writings on the ethics of care of the self [53].

metadata.2: Knowing through Quantification

__data__.text:
For Foucault, 
individuals should constantly engage in a moral and ethical project to achieve happiness, wisdom, 
health, and wellbeing [27].

metadata.2: Knowing through Quantification

__data__.text:
When Foucault conceived the idea of self-knowledge and care of the 
self [27], he pointed to individuals’ agency in developing knowledge about themselves against the 
backdrop of the prevalence of power relations.

metadata.2: Knowing through Quantification

__data__.text:
Foucault further discussed technologies of the self 
through which individuals could develop self-knowledge, such as self-examination with respect

to thoughts in correspondence to reality, the way our thoughts related to rules, and the relation 
between the hidden thought and an inner impurity [28].

metadata.2: Knowing through Quantification

__data__.text:
Building upon the idea of technologies 
of the self, researchers have explored how digital technologies could become a technology of the 
self as people exert their agency in discovering and transforming their selves [41,52].

metadata.2: Knowing through Quantification

__data__.text: In personal informatics, one primary application field of the practices of self-quantification,

metadata.2: Knowing through Quantification

__data__.text:
individuals collect, analyze, and reflect upon many types of personal information such as bank 
statements, email history, and health information [49].

metadata.2: Knowing through Quantification

__data__.text:
Particularly in self-tracking, individuals 
start to quantify and monitor themselves for many reasons such as better health condition, 
physical or mental performance, new stimuli, or socializing [12,53].

metadata.2: Knowing through Quantification

__data__.text: But numerical representation, the output of quantification, has long been cited for issues such

metadata.2: Knowing through Quantification

__data__.text:
as a reductionist approach [65,66], removal of contextual information [21], and complex 
psychological processes related to interpretation of the data [11].

metadata.2: Knowing through Quantification

__data__.text:
Ultimately, quantification 
entails categorization and involves qualitative judgment [10,14,63], demanding closer attention to 
the entanglement between quantification and the values beneath design decisions [7].

metadata.2: Knowing through Quantification

__data__.text: Inspired by John Langshaw Austin who analyzed words as deeds [3], Espeland and Stevens

metadata.2: Knowing through Quantification

__data__.text: suggested that numbers should be regarded as deeds as well [26].

metadata.2: Knowing through Quantification

__data__.text:
According to them, numbers 
are acts of communication whose meanings and functions depend deeply upon ‘grammars’ and 
‘vocabularies’ developed over time through use, and should not be reduced to a narrow 
instrumentality [26].

metadata.2: Knowing through Quantification

__data__.text:
They proposed one important distinction between forms of quantification 
which is those that mark and those that commensurate.

metadata.2: Knowing through Quantification

__data__.text:
Numbers that mark are used to identify 
entities, such as numbers on a license plate.

metadata.2: Knowing through Quantification

__data__.text:
Numbers that commensurate are to evaluate or 
measure different objects with a common metric [25].

metadata.2: Knowing through Quantification

__data__.text:
For Espeland and Stevens, commensuration 
is a process that creates a specific relationship among objects by transforming all difference into 
quantity, thus requiring considerable social and intellectual investment [25].

metadata.2: Knowing through Quantification

__data__.text:
Measures can thus 
influence and discipline people, or shape and reinforce existing categories [26].

metadata.2: Knowing through Quantification

__data__.text:
Therefore, 
quantification can have multiple meanings and purposes across contexts.

metadata.2: Knowing through Quantification

__data__.text:
To understand a 
specific form of quantification, we shall study the context through which numbers are generated, 
sorted, and interpreted through numeracy and broadly shared methodological standards.

__data__.text: 3.2 Trust and Collaborative Traces in Virtual Teamwork

metadata.2: Trust and Collaborative Traces in Virtual Teamwork

__data__.text:
Understanding challenges and design opportunities for supporting virtual teams has been a 
primary research strand in both CSCW and organizational studies for a long time.

metadata.2: Trust and Collaborative Traces in Virtual Teamwork

__data__.text:
An important 
foundational element for successful virtual teamwork is trust.

metadata.2: Trust and Collaborative Traces in Virtual Teamwork

__data__.text:
Tseng and Fogg considered trust as 
“a positive belief about the perceived reliability of, dependability of, and confidence in a person, 
object, or process” [75].

metadata.2: Trust and Collaborative Traces in Virtual Teamwork

__data__.text:
In virtual teams, members may not have a history of interpersonal 
interactions and communication through which trust is developed in collocated collaboration.

metadata.2: Trust and Collaborative Traces in Virtual Teamwork

__data__.text:
Thus organizational and management research has explores many facets of trust formation in 
virtual teams, such as managers’ and leaders’ strategic actions [30], goal setting [35], the 
interplay between the cognitive and affective dimensions [40], functional diversity [62], and the 
relationship between monitoring and trust [18,67].

metadata.2: Trust and Collaborative Traces in Virtual Teamwork

__data__.text: To foster trust in virtual teamwork, a rising body of CSCW research, often focused on the

__data__.text:
setting of global software development, has turned to mechanisms that support teammates to 
follow and monitor one another’s work status and history.

metadata.2: Trust and Collaborative Traces in Virtual Teamwork

__data__.text:
For example, Froehlich and Dourish 
implemented a visualization system that provided a view of the dynamic software process, and 
reported that this system providers developers meaningful information and context of 
development process [29].

Regarding

__data__.text: 3.3 Participatory Surveillance in Online Games

metadata.2: Participatory Surveillance in Online Games

__data__.text:
As players use quantification tools to monitor both their and their teammates’ performance, 
quantitative measures support simplifying, classifying, comparing, and evaluating, the core 
means of disciplinary power [69].

metadata.2: Participatory Surveillance in Online Games

__data__.text:
Particularly, LoL can be analyzed from the lens of “surveillance 
games,” which Albrechtslund and Dubbeld defined as ones “that use data processing technologies 
to provide or enhance entertainment, thereby appropriating surveillance devices for their own 
hedonistic purposes” [2].

metadata.2: Participatory Surveillance in Online Games

__data__.text:
Later Albrechtslund proposed the notion of participatory surveillance [1] 
to argue for the social and playful aspects of surveillance, which has been less discussed in 
previous surveillance literature that focuses primarily upon the negative and repressive aspect of 
surveillance.

metadata.2: Participatory Surveillance in Online Games

__data__.text: However, video games are not just for play, entertainment, and relaxation.

metadata.2: Participatory Surveillance in Online Games

__data__.text: Yee noted that

metadata.2: Participatory Surveillance in Online Games

__data__.text:
video games blur the boundaries of work and play as online games players invest lots of time 
(average 20 hours a week), perform “an assortment of clerical tasks, logistical planning and 
management,” the very same thing they do in their offices [80].

metadata.2: Participatory Surveillance in Online Games

__data__.text:
Extensive video game research 
has reported how players carried out systematic and carefully planned efforts in order to make 
progressions and achievements [4,44,57,72].

metadata.2: Participatory Surveillance in Online Games

__data__.text:
Video game research in the CSCW literature has 
developed a deep understanding of video game play as a form of collaborative work [37,58,59].

metadata.2: Participatory Surveillance in Online Games

__data__.text: Putting together the idea of participatory, playful surveillance and that of the blurring

metadata.2: Participatory Surveillance in Online Games

__data__.text:
boundary of work and play, we observe a tension between the pleasurable and the serious, work-
like framings of monitoring self and teammates.

metadata.2: Participatory Surveillance in Online Games

__data__.text:
Stressing the importance of willingness to 
participate in surveillance, Whitson noted that “the moment you understand that you are 
working, you are not playing… But for it to be experienced as play, everyone needs to be a 
willing participant” [79].

metadata.2: Participatory Surveillance in Online Games

__data__.text:
LoL players cannot be considered as “willing participants,” as the game 
company, Riot Games, owns and decides to make available players’ data.

metadata.2: Participatory Surveillance in Online Games

__data__.text:
In this regard, our paper 
contributes to a deeper understanding of the relationship between work and play in the context 
of surveillance practice.
4 METHODS

This paper is based upon a multi-year ethnographic study of League of Legends from October 
2011 to the time of this study.

The ethnographic project was initiated with a general purpose of 
understanding players’ social experiences within the game community.

The project has gradually 
developed into two distinct but related strands including governance [45] and player experience 
[43,44].
This paper belongs to the second strand.

The first author conducted participant 
observation in the game’s North American server as well as numerous related online venues, 
following the idea of multi-sited ethnography [54].

The first author played between 700 to 1000 
ranked or normal matches per year since 2011 (except the year of 2015), ranked at Platinum by 
the time of this study, and participated in and observed player discussions in LoL-focused online

forums hosted on Riot Games’ server as well as general social media sites such as Reddit.

The 
first author also frequented video-based social media platforms such as YouTube and Twitch, a 
living streaming site, which were frequently discussed among players as primary venues for 
watching and learning from the gameplay of professional eSports or highly skilled players.

The 
first author obtained knowledge of these quantification tools through this long-term engagement 
in the game, and frequently used these tools to inform his own play.

Extensive fieldnotes and 
screenshots were taken regarding numerous aspects of social life and player experience with the 
game through participant observation.
The project was not about quantification from the very beginning.
While doing ethnographic

work, the first author also conducted two rounds of interviews prior to this study of 
quantification.

The first round was conducted in 2012 and 2013 with a focus on how player 
perceived collaboration in LoL.

The second round was conducted in 2014 and 2015, concerning 
how players learned and improved their ranks in game.

Both served as individual research 
projects.

It is important to note that the first two rounds prior to this study did not have a focus 
on quantification.

However, the opening questions such as how you improved your skill in the 
game often encouraged players to talk about their experiences with numerous quantification 
tools that they had used, with op.gg being the latest and most frequently cited among the study 
participants.

The first two rounds of interviews, as well as the first author’s own experience, 
inspired this study to investigate how LoL players used quantification in their play.
The latest round of interview was conducted in February and March 2018, with a focus on the
use of quantification tools in gameplay.

During this round, we conducted semi-structured, open-
ended interviews with 22 LoL players with diverse ranks distributed across Bronze, Silver, Gold, 
Platinum, and Diamond.

They all reported playing for at least one year and being familiar with 
one or more quantification tools.

The interviews were started with the following open-ended 
questions: 1) can you talk about when you started playing the game?

2) how do you improve 
your skill in the game?
3) how did you come to know the existence of the quantification tools?

4) 
when do you use these tools?
5) how do these tools influence your gameplay?

6) how do you 
know other players use these tools?
The interviews were conducted either through in-game messaging function, email, or skype in
English, and lasted between 20 and 40 minutes.

We manually transcribed these interviews for 
later analysis.

Combining previous interviews where players mentioned their use of 
quantification tools, and the latest round of 22 interviews focused on these tools, we had a total 
number of 68 interview transcripts.

A substantial portion of the 68 interviews mentioned 
quantification.

However, when reporting data in this paper, we draw primarily from the latest 
round of 22 interviews, as well as one from an interview conducted in 2015, because of their data 
richness and topical relevance.

demographic information of 23 participants whose interviews were actually used in this paper.
We used thematic analysis [6] to analyze our data in an inductive approach [61] to identify
themes that are strongly linked to the data themselves.

The dataset for analysis included all the 
68 interview transcripts, as well as forum discussions, fieldnotes, screenshots taken in the past 
few years.

Two researchers (including the first author) familiar with LoL participated in this 
analysis process.

We first familiarized ourselves with data with the initial analytic interests in the 
role of quantification in supporting gameplay.

Each researcher immersed himself or herself in the 
data through reading back and forth and marking ideas.

During this iterative process, the two 
researchers had regular meetings on a daily basis to discuss ideas.

Each of us then started 
generating an individual list of initial codes through our whole dataset, after which we compared

5 FINDINGS

League of Legends players used various quantification tools to quantify themselves as well as 
others for the purpose of progression in the game.

Players frequently engaged in interpretation 
and re-interpretation of their numbers, as well as negotiation of numbers’ meanings in team 
communication.

Quantification and interpretation involved much cognitive work and invoked 
emotional reactions, and sometimes disrupted virtual teamwork.

Some players reflected upon 
what constituted proper use of quantification.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: 5.1 Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: LoL players acknowledged the great diversity in the numbers provided by the quantification tools.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: They, however, stressed that numbers were not self-evident.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
Players saw various meanings and 
implications of numbers.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
They tried to interpret numbers by drawing from their situated 
knowledge in LoL.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
5.1.1 Capturing Various Meanings and Implications of Numbers 
We observed that numbers were frequently cited as markers of skill and performance.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
Each 
participant that we interviewed had developed standards for determining the meaning of a 
number.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: For example, a participant told us:

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
I had 85% win rate on Ekko [a LoL champion], it was amazing… until they [Riot Games] made the 
changes [new game patch] to remnants of the watchers [an in-game item].

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
My KDA 
[kill/death/assist ratio] before the changes were 4.50.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
[P1] 
In this quote, P1 explained how his numbers associated with Ekko were negatively influenced

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: by LoL’s recent patch.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
He also expressed high satisfaction with his previous records associated 
with Ekko, where he considered ‘85% win rate’ and ‘4.5 KDA’ indicators of good performance.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: In a similar vein, P2 asked us to visit his op.gg profile by saying “check my lux [a LoL champion]

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
win rate on op.gg… over 60%!” P3 told us that “200 CS [creep score] in 20 minutes… it is my best 
record.” In these cases, numbers that fell within certain ranges had supplied players joy and pride, 
because these numbers were considered both “good” and difficult to achieve.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: According to our study participants, numbers did not just represent gaming skills.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: They could

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: also reveal other qualities such as temperament, mindset, motivation, and desire to win.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
For 
example, a participant noted how she sometimes could discern players’ mental stability:

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
If you see a player on a massive loss streak like 1:8, likely that the player is tilted… Your game is 
not going to end up well.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
[P5] 
“Tilt” or “tilted” means that a player’s mental state is declining, which is likely to negatively

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: impact player performance.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
For P5, the numbers of wins and losses in the recent match history of 
a player did not simply communicate the player’s previous performance.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
The numbers also 
strongly suggested the likelihood of the player’s chance to win in next match.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
Many of our 
participants expressed a similar viewpoint with P5 that a player who was experiencing or had 
just experienced was likely to do badly in game.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
Beneath this logic was players’ many personal 
experiences with a “vicious cycle,” that losing a game caused negative emotions such as 
distresses and frustrations, which in turn impacted their future games in negative ways.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
5.1.2 Interpreting Numbers in Light of Situated Knowledge 
Our participants stressed that situated knowledge of the game was key to proper interpretation 
of numbers.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
One type of situated knowledge of the game commonly cited by our participants is 
the knowledge regarding the different modes of the game.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: P7 said:

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: A high KDA in normal is nice, but it says little about skill… [players] don’t try hard in normals.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
[p7] 
“Normals” refer to the normal game mode that is not ranked, in which players tend to be more

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: casual.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
In normal mode, players tended to try new play styles and care less about winning, and 
high KDA could happen because the player was trying powerful champions while others weak 
ones.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
Experienced players like P7 were acutely aware of the distinction between the two game 
modes, and utilized this situated knowledge to make more accurate assessment.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: Another type of situated knowledge of the game frequently brought up by our participants is

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: the knowledge of different champion’s mechanism.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
When asked what “win rate” would look 
good, P5 explained:

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
It depends on the champion… I have above 55% win rate with Zyra [a LoL champion] and 
generally feel like I’m carrying with her… but a Yasuo [a LoL champion] below 60% win rate is 
bad.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: Yasuos either solo win the game… or feed and ruin the game.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
[P5] 
In LoL, Zyra and Yasuo have different play styles, with the latter being high-risk, high-reward.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: Therefore, Yasuo’s impact on match results tends to be highly polarized.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
With knowledge of 
different champions, P5 had developed more situated interpretations taking into account different 
play styles associated with champions.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
In this way, a number like 55% win rate could have 
different meanings per context.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
In addition, P5’s explanation indicated how she gradually learned 
how to interpret numbers through her own experiences.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
Her general observation that she 
contributed a lot to teamwork (i.e.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
“carrying”) was an important reason behind her belief that 55% 
was a good number for Zyra.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
Similarly, her experiences with Yasuo teammates deeply influenced 
her interpretation of Yasuo win rate.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: In addition, our participants also stressed that gameplay across the wide spectrum of ranks

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: was vastly different in terms of player decision making, team composition, and competitiveness.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
Therefore, they described how their understanding of these differences influenced their 
interpretation of numbers.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: For example, P14 told us:

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
My Diamond friend dies averagely 6-7 times…he said he had to takes risks… [but] he almost never 
dies playing on my account [in Silver].

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
[P14] 
P14 narrated a sharp distinction between Diamond and Silver, and how such distinction in

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
gameplay could result in different numbers: Diamond matches are more competitive and intense, 
leaving little room for players’ decision making.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
Therefore, P14’s friend could perceive more risks 
when playing at Diamond.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
However, the same player encountered few challenges at Silver, and 
thus “almost never dies.” P17 remembered that his average CS decreased as he climbed from Gold 
to Platinum, because he encountered more “aggressive lane opponents” that would prevent him 
from getting more CS.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
Like P14 and P17, many of our participants noted how the intensity and 
competitiveness of different ranks could influence numbers.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: Through playing LoL, players kept learning about various aspects of LoL that would offer new

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: angles to interpret numbers.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
Each player’ set of situated knowledge was gradually built upon 
their own experiences.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
Therefore, the derivation of qualitative insights from numbers was 
cognitively challenging to many players.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
Online forums became a place where players learned 
from each other about how to interpret numbers.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
We learned about this social activity on the 
‘/r/leagueoflegends’ subreddit from several of our participants.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: Here is an example:

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:

93:11

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: Post: Post a link to your OP.GG profile and get advice from the community!

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
I believed it could be nice if high elo players could share some advice to low elo scrubs like myself 
:) 
Player 1: My CS is trash [shared link to a op.gg player profile; removed for anonymity] 
Player 2: Miss fortune [LoL champion] and Ashe [LoL champion] were good picks for your rank.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: But you should consider playing more Annie [LoL champion] instead of Orianna [LoL champion].

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: This way you can both improve CS and focus more on the game rather than csing.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: Elo is an alternative term for player rank.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: In this excerpt, Player 1 invited critique upon their

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text: own profile.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
While Player 1 expressed one of their numbers (i.e., CS) was poor, Player 2 gave 
concrete advice on improving CS as well as more general suggestions regarding how to improve 
skill.

metadata.2: Nuanced and Situated Interpretation of Numbers

__data__.text:
Player 2’s analysis was based on a combination of Player 1’s numbers as well as Player 2’s 
understandings of different champions’ strengths and weaknesses.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: 5.2 Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
Through the interpretation of publicly available data, LoL players conveniently reflected on their 
own performance, and learnt about their teammates and opponents.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
They used this knowledge to 
inform their gameplay.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
They could coordinate with their teammates to optimize their gameplay 
strategies.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: LoL players’ reliance on quantification for gameplay was manifested in a common linguistic

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: pattern in the community.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
We observed numerous instances where terms denoting quantification 
tools such as ‘op.gg’ and ‘lolking’ were used as not only nouns but also as verbs.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
Players 
frequently used “op.gg me” or “lolking the player” to denote the practice of checking someone on 
specific quantification tools.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
An example is “If you op.gg me, you can see I win almost 70% of my 
Jarvan IV [a LoL champion] games.”

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
5.2.1 Developing Self-Knowledge and Improving Performance 
As players believed that these numbers indicated their own performance and skill, they took 
advantage of the quantification tools to develop insights into their own gameplay.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
P1 told us that 
“I mainly use op.gg to check my KDA, win rate, and ....

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
I just like to track my progress to get better.” 
In this way, players sought to develop self-knowledge through quantification.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
On Reddit, a player 
shared their op.gg profile, and narrated a story of progression through numbers:

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
Just climbed from Plat 4 to Diamond 5 playing only Fiddlestick (86% winrate over 28 games) 
[shared link to a op.gg player profile; removed for anonymity] ... started tryharding with my 
beloved main and had this massive win streak (24 W - 4 L).

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: “Main” refers to the champion that a player plays the most.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: In the above quote, the player’s

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: main was Fiddlestick.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: The player expressed excitement about improvement in the game.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: All of our participants mentioned using quantification to keep informed and seek self-

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: improvement.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: For instance, P11 said:

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
My Janna’s [a LoL champion] KDA was embarrassing with 5.1 deaths per game… because most 
jannas have less than three deaths.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
My janna died too much because I played in a wrong way… I 
watched guides to learn builds, matchups, and itemization.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: According to P11, his interpretation of his Janna KDA was that his performance was poor and

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: he needed improvement.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: He proceeded to learn and improve himself.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
5.2.2 Assessing and Choosing Teammates 
Participants used numbers to observe the status and skill level of their friends.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
They then used 
this observation to invite skilled friends to play together.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: For example, P4 said:

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
93:12 
 Y. Kou & X. Gui

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: I have made some friends in league…I would look them up [on quantification tools].

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
I know their 
best roles in the game… who I want to duo [playing with a friend] with for my placements…who I 
only play norms [normal mode] with.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
[P4] 
P4 shared with us how he used quantification to develop knowledge about his friends.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: Placements refer to placement matches that have a major influence over players’ rank.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
Building 
on the knowledge of his friends, P4 would strategize his play for the purpose of progression in 
game.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
In competitive matches, especially placements where stakes were higher, he wanted to 
play with friends who he believed to be highly skilled.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
In casual scenes, he would be more open 
to playing with friends of different skill levels.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: Players could perceive whether their teammates desired to win through interpretation of

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: numbers.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
For example, P10 said that “you know your teammates don’t want to win when they 
pick a champ they are bad at.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: Chances are you already lost in champion select.”

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: Players also mentioned how numbers told them whether their teammates could be potentially

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: toxic in game.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
In an interview via the in-game messaging tool of LoL client, P1 sent the URL to an 
op.gg profile and said:

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: Just check this guy.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
His Teemo [a LoL champion] has over 8 deaths each game with only two or 
three kills… Those players just feed and flame junglers [a role in game] all time.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
When he locked 
in Teemo, I insta dodged.” 
“Dodge,” or “queue dodge,” refers to the action of closing the game client to cancel a match.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
Dodge is not against LoL’s terms of service, but it wastes the computing resources for generating 
a match and causes delays to other players.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
Riot Games discourages this behavior by deducting a 
small amount of ranking points per time of dodge, which is less consequential than the decrease 
of ranking points if losing a match.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
Therefore, players would calculate benefits and risks when 
deciding whether to dodge.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
Without actually playing the game with his teammate, P1 was 
already confident in telling about a teammate’s potential negative behaviors in game.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
Interpretation of the numbers associated with Teemo suggested the teammate’s potential poor 
performance in the next game.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
Such interpretation, combined with past experiences with Teemo 
players, supported P1’s reasoning process leading to the conclusion that his teammate could be a 
toxic player that he would avoid teaming up with, and thus he decided to dodge the game to 
avoid the risk of losing ranking points.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:

Participants used their numbers as evidence to support their verbal claim for certain roles in team.

I’m really good at a couple ap carries [roles in 
game].

I also paste my 
op.gg link so they can click.

Sometimes it works, my teammates would give their role to me… not 
every time though.

[P13] 
In this example, P13 talked about how he shared his profile with his teammates in order to

__data__.text: convince his teammates that he should play the role of mid5.

Quantification here was used to 
enhance the legitimacy of his claim.

For this use of quantification to work, the player must be 
aware of the generally accepted criteria, or the common ground, for determining high or low 
performance of particular champions and roles.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

Having experienced similar situations but on the 
other side, P7 told us that “I use op.gg when someone is asking for my role.

But if someone wants to mid with a 11% Kass [a LoL

In this excerpt, the player vividly described a scenario where they tried to persuade their

__data__.text:
teammate to pick a champion that the latter was good at, evidenced in the combination of

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

For this player, these combined measures unambiguously pointed

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
Therefore, the player took action for 
the purpose of improving their winning chance.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: Lastly, quantification supported them to strategize their gameplay for the best chances of

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: winning games.

Most of our participants looked up their teammates and used this knowledge to 
customize their play style.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

champion] top.

I knew if I could give him a good start, he 
would be able to snowball and carry the game.

I came to his lane right after my 
red buff and gave him a kill….

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

He and I carried the game, even though other lanes were a bit 
behind.

[P12] 
The jungle role in LoL is a leadership role, requiring the player to decide which teammates to

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: help with and what objectives to pursue for the best outcome.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
For P12, the analysis of his 
teammate’s statistics informed his play style.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
The subsequent win confirmed his previous theory 
about how to strategize gameplay based on interpretation of teammates’ numbers.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
5.2.4 Exploiting and Constraining Opponents 
Our participants talked about various ways of drawing from quantification to tailor strategies to 
constrain their opponents.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
On the one hand, P17 told us that “I’m gonna try hard to not lose to my 
lane opponent who is having a losing streak.” In this example, P17 described a scenario where he 
noticed his lane opponent’s losing streak, and surmised that his lane opponent might be “tilted.” 
P17 wanted to take advantage of this perceived weakness of the lane opponent.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: On the other hand, players could perceive their opponents as skillful and superior.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: This

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text: perception encouraged players to adjust their play styles to be more conservative.

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
Here is an 
excerpt from an online forum conversation:

metadata.2: Using Quantified Data to Strategize Gameplay

__data__.text:
If I see they have 300 games played with said champ in rank, I know they're at minimum 
experienced.

__data__.text: 5.3 Negotiating with Quantification

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
In the first two sections, we reported how LoL players sought to rationalize and utilize their 
interpretation of numbers, for the purpose of progression in game and optimization of teamwork.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
However, beyond the rational and instrumental use of quantification, players also had emotional 
investment into their numbers.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
We observed that many players struggled to strike a balance 
between their amount of attention to their numbers and just having “fun” in game.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
Many of our 
study participants mentioned what constituted the proper use of quantification.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
5.3.1 Experiencing Negative Consequences Associated with Quantification 
Our study participants stressed that using quantification was useful in competitive play, and they 
felt the social pressure to do so.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text: P11, for instance, stated that:

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
I have to use these tools to compete with people who already use them… it is publicly available 
and whoever doesn’t use it is at a disadvantage.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
[P11] 
From a practical point of view, P11 stressed how quantification was already an integral

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text: component of ranked gameplay in LoL.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
As an individual, he could only comply with this practice 
to keep up with other LoL players.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text: Our study participants also perceived various negative consequences associated with their use

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text: of quantification.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
At the individual level, misuse of quantification could cause negative emotions 
such as distress and anxiety among players.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
At the team level, discussions of numbers could 
cause conflicts and tensions.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
Stress and Anxiety among Individual Players 
Players viewed numbers as direct indicators of their performance, and developed judgements as 
to what numbers were superior.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
Pursuit of better numbers became their conscious goal while 
playing games.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text: For instance, P6 mentioned that “I try to keep my deaths under 4 each game.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
Good 
players don’t die a lot.” Like P6 said, qualitative marks such as “good players” were consciously 
related to a specific numerical range.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
Poor numbers, on the other hand, could cause negative 
emotions among players.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
P14 told us that “I have an embarrassing win rate with Dr Mundo… under 
40%… I’m terrible with tanks.”

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text: The attention on numbers and improving numbers also caused much stress and anxiety

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text: among several participants.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text: P19 told us:

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
Most times I’m good… But it was so stressful when I noticed that my recent win rate has dropped 
below 40%...

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text: I feel I suck at this game.

In this way, the player indicated that the existing set of statistics did

Participants also mentioned checking their teammates, and sometimes became unsatisfied by

Such dissatisfaction could surface in communication with teammates, 
causing conflicts and tensions within teams.

__data__.text: For example, P21 mentioned:

__data__.text: 5.3.2 Exploring Proper Relationships with Quantification

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text: Some LoL players perceived the downside of using quantification.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text: They started to stress the

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text: idea of using quantification properly.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
P17, for example, said that “[you] can’t be obsessed with 
op.gg.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text: It’s just a tool.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
It’s only useful if you know what it is and how to use it.” P17 discussed the 
proper relationship between player and quantification.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
He noticed the potential psychological 
burden associated with use of quantification if a player dedicated too much attention to it.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
He 
pointed to the instrumental value of quantification, and stressed players’ own responsibility and 
capacity in proper use.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text: One common way our participants used to cope with the psychological burden was non-use.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
For example, P6 noted that “stop using it if it psychs you out.” P6 saw non-use as a way of 
avoiding negative emotions.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text: Some players reported concrete benefits of non-use.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
P21 told us that 
“I simply stopped.

__data__.text:
I am feeling much better now and my rank has moved up as well.” Another 
participant P22 reported:

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text: I used to check my teammates and got tilted a lot.

__data__.text:
Nowadays I don’t do it any more… I start to 
focus on my own play because this is the only thing I can control and improve...

I learn more each 
game.

__data__.text: However, they changed their

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

behavior upon noticing the negative aspects of overusing quantification, in order to take care of 
their own psychological wellbeing.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
Their descriptions sought to articulate a causal relationship 
between non-use and subsequent positive experiences, in terms of increased rank and learning.

__data__.text: 6 DISCUSSION

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
In this paper, we reported an ethnographic account of quantification in the player community of 
League of Legends.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
The player community celebrates a highly competitive culture where players 
aspire to higher ranks, and admire high-ranking players, especially professional players, which 
has been commonly found in eSports gaming communities [39,44,73,77].

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
Therefore, it is perhaps 
unsurprising that numbers and quantification play an indispensable role in this community.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
The 
complexity of quantification practices is conditioned by the publicity of every single member’s 
statistics accumulated across multiple years, an abundance of advanced quantification tools, and 
years of development of a culture of interpretation of numbers.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
All players are involved, 
regardless of their willingness.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
Players who refuse to use quantification are still subject to the 
quantification, evaluation, and judgment from their teammates and opponents.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text: In many ways, players’ own accounts and forums discussions are in alignment with the ideal

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
of developing “self-knowledge through numbers,” as they adeptly used quantification to develop 
knowledge about themselves as well as their teammates and opponents in order to win matches 
and subsequently improve ranks.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
However, quantification could also take a toll on players, both 
cognitively and emotionally, as players also struggled to find a balance in their relationship with 
numbers, realizing that improper use of quantification could can distress them and negatively 
impact virtual teamwork.

metadata.2: Negotiating with Quantification

__data__.text:
Next, we discuss implications of the multiplicity of perspectives on 
numbers, the relationship between quantification and trust, and players’ notion of proper use in 
relation to self-knowledge.

metadata.2: A Complex Dance Between Interpretive Flexibility and Numerical Authority

__data__.text: 6.1 A Complex Dance Between Interpretive Flexibility and Numerical Authority

metadata.2: A Complex Dance Between Interpretive Flexibility and Numerical Authority

__data__.text:
Our findings about the nuances and complexities in players’ experiences with numbers resonates 
with Espeland and Stevens that numbers have multiple meanings and purposes [26].

metadata.2: A Complex Dance Between Interpretive Flexibility and Numerical Authority

__data__.text:
Numbers 
generated through quantification had multiple meanings to participants.

metadata.2: A Complex Dance Between Interpretive Flexibility and Numerical Authority

__data__.text:
These meanings were 
constructed based on players’ interpretations, experiences, and discussions with other players 
within the community.

metadata.2: A Complex Dance Between Interpretive Flexibility and Numerical Authority

__data__.text:
The numbers could be an explicit representation of player skill and 
performance, evident in how study participants took pride in their high win rate champions in 
interviews.

metadata.2: A Complex Dance Between Interpretive Flexibility and Numerical Authority

__data__.text:
Participants also believed that they could capture many other personal qualities such 
as mental state and desire to win through scrutiny of statistics such as win rate and match 
history.

metadata.2: A Complex Dance Between Interpretive Flexibility and Numerical Authority

__data__.text: Numbers also possessed multiple types of purposes, which could analyzed as “deeds” [26].

metadata.2: A Complex Dance Between Interpretive Flexibility and Numerical Authority

__data__.text:
They not only described what a player had achieved in the past, but also advised in-game actions, 
and predicted whether the player would either succeed or fail in the future.

metadata.2: A Complex Dance Between Interpretive Flexibility and Numerical Authority

__data__.text:
Our findings reported 
many accounts where numbers inspired players to predict match results and strategize gameplay.

metadata.2: A Complex Dance Between Interpretive Flexibility and Numerical Authority

__data__.text: In Table 2, we summarize representative types of numbers and their purposes.

metadata.2: A Complex Dance Between Interpretive Flexibility and Numerical Authority

list of types is infeasible due to page limit.)

metadata.2: A Complex Dance Between Interpretive Flexibility and Numerical Authority

__data__.text:
However, it is important to note that numbers did not 
work alone, and sometimes players triangulated multiple numbers to develop an explanation.

__data__.text: Such multiplicity of meanings and purposes highlights the vast flexibility of interpreting

metadata.2: A Complex Dance Between Interpretive Flexibility and Numerical Authority

__data__.text: numbers in LoL.

metadata.2: A Complex Dance Between Interpretive Flexibility and Numerical Authority

__data__.text:
Such interpretive flexibility of numbers is rooted in players’ diverse sets of 
situated knowledge.

metadata.2: A Complex Dance Between Interpretive Flexibility and Numerical Authority

__data__.text:
For example, P5 and Yasuo players would have very different opinions about 
whether a win rate of 55% was good enough on Yasuo.

metadata.2: A Complex Dance Between Interpretive Flexibility and Numerical Authority

__data__.text:
P15 once disagreed with her teammates 
upon the interpretation of KDA.

metadata.2: A Complex Dance Between Interpretive Flexibility and Numerical Authority

__data__.text: Importantly, beneath these disagreements over how to interpret numbers was in fact the

metadata.2: A Complex Dance Between Interpretive Flexibility and Numerical Authority

__data__.text: authority many LoL players granted to the numbers and quantification tools.

metadata.2: A Complex Dance Between Interpretive Flexibility and Numerical Authority

__data__.text:
Authority, 
according to Weber, is a form of power that is legitimate without either coercion or threat of 
violence [78].

metadata.2: A Complex Dance Between Interpretive Flexibility and Numerical Authority

__data__.text:
Such numerical authority resided in many characteristics of quantification tools: 
the overwhelming amount of numbers that implied their comprehensiveness, the archival of 
complete historical data that expressed a sense of continuum, and the fast response time that 
communicated reliability.

metadata.2: A Complex Dance Between Interpretive Flexibility and Numerical Authority

__data__.text:
Numerical authority also rested in players’ own practices, such as their 
sustained use and learning to use, and their discussions with others regarding how to use 
quantification.

metadata.2: A Complex Dance Between Interpretive Flexibility and Numerical Authority

__data__.text: Numerical authority guided players to develop categories such as the dichotomy between

metadata.2: A Complex Dance Between Interpretive Flexibility and Numerical Authority

__data__.text: “good” and “bad,” albeit in a distributed and informal fashion.

metadata.2: A Complex Dance Between Interpretive Flexibility and Numerical Authority

__data__.text:
Still, players’ classification 
activities resonated with what Bowker and Star warned about the ramifications of 
institutionalized and formalized classification systems [5].

metadata.2: A Complex Dance Between Interpretive Flexibility and Numerical Authority

__data__.text:
For example, the South Africa racial 
classification system sorted individuals into four major racial groups which intrinsically 
supported the ruling classes’ identity and legitimacy, but Bowker and Star found individual cases 
that did not comply with the legal and technical-scientific delineations [5].

In our study, players 
agreed upon the purposes of various numbers, but were rarely unanimous on how to interpret 
them.

__data__.text:

pushback as players rejected to be classified as “bad” players.

__data__.text: 6.2 Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text:
Resonating with many game scholars’ observation of the blurring boundary between work and 
play [56,57,80], LoL players’ participation also involved intense work in terms of the sheet 
amount of knowledge to learn about, necessary attention, energy, and techniques to guarantee 
their performance.

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text:
Therefore, quantification did not simply enhance or challenge LoL’s virtual 
teamwork.

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text:
Rather, it had an intensifying and complicating effect by demanding cognitive 
engagement from all players who were already “working.” Therefore, there were parallels 
between the use of quantification in LoL teams and collaborative traces in global software 
development.

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text: Building upon prior discussions of the utility of collaborative traces in developing trust in

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text:
virtual teams [55,74], in this paper, we found similar cases such as P12’s example where LoL 
players developed better understandings of and trust in their teammates, and proceeded to 
strategize around competent teammates.

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text:
However, these cases were oftentimes ideal scenarios 
where teammates perceived each other’s numbers in an acceptable range and were willing to 
coordinate.

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text: Discussing how trust can be developed or enhanced by quantification speaks to the notion of

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text: instrumental trust [8].

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text:
Instrumental trust rests upon instrumental rational efficiency of the 
system, or the instrumental value of quantification to players in our study.

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text:
However, Brown sees 
trust as “inherently irrational and affective,” because trust is a response to uncertainty, which is 
then linked to potential anxiety [8].

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text:
Therefore, the instrumental perspective is insufficient in 
understanding the relationship between quantification and trust.

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text:
Players could easily develop 
trust or expectations in their teammates with superior numbers that had a convincing power.

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text:
However, our findings about individuals’ anxiety as well as team-level tensions and conflicts 
reflected the inherent irrationality and affection in the process in which players used 
quantification with ensuing trust or distrust.

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text:
Therefore, our findings point to nuances and 
complexities of trust beyond the instrumental perspective.

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text: Niklas Luhmann proposed the notion of communicative trust [51].

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text: According to Luhmann,

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text:
communicative trust has three qualities: the process of trust requires mutual commitment as two 
sides must be involved; the building up of trust depends on easily interpretable situations and 
possibility of communication; and trust can only be offered and accepted, not demanded [51].

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text: Indeed, our findings resonate with this communicative aspect of trust.

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text:
To cope with the trust 
issues in their teamwork, players frequently performed various communicative acts.

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text:
They could 
draw upon their own numbers to legitimize a claim, to confront their teammates’ decisions which 
they deemed unhelpful to team, or to negotiate strategies.

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text:
Through communication, trust and 
distrust could be expressed, established, enhanced, or diminished.

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text: The communicative aspect of trust was heightened in LoL teams in comparison to previously

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text: studied global software development teams, for several reasons.

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text:
First, despite the many parallels 
between work and play, LoL’s teamwork environment often lacks professional etiquette and 
courtesy that would be more typical in workplace [17].

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text:
By contrast, LoL is an online game where 
interpersonal aggression is a common theme [43,48,71].

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text:
Therefore, it is perhaps unsurprising that 
almost all of our participants reportedly spoke out in game, expressing concerns about trust.

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text:
Second, LoL is a highly competitive team-based game, and players need to rely on their 
teammates to win [43].

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text:
Therefore, players often have scrupulous attention to their teammates’ 
performance and status.

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text:
Third, LoL players considered their numbers as part of their identity and 
endeavored to improve them [44], much like prior studies of how social media users made efforts

__data__.text:

__data__.text: to improve their numerical representations [22,38].

metadata.2: Quantification and the Communicative Aspect of Trust

__data__.text:
Taking pride in their own numbers, players 
might defend against teammates’ questions and doubts.

__data__.text: The perspective of communicative trust also invites reflections upon possible hidden

__data__.text: disagreements and tensions when researching and implementing collective traces for trust.

It is 
likely that people have diverse interpretations of capacity and performance, even in ideal 
scenarios where through predefined measurements collective traces are reported to enhance trust.

Unrecognition of invisible disagreements and tensions could have a deteriorating effect in the 
long run.

It is important to investigate what narratives or perspectives are preferred, and what 
are rendered invisible or marginalized.

metadata.2: Proper Use of Quantification

__data__.text: 6.3 Proper Use of Quantification

metadata.2: Proper Use of Quantification

__data__.text:
Our findings reported a variety of negative consequences and burdens as perceived by our 
participants.

metadata.2: Proper Use of Quantification

__data__.text:
There were stress and anxiety as the individual level, and conflicts and tensions at 
the team level.

metadata.2: Proper Use of Quantification

__data__.text:
These negative consequences echoed a few HCI studies of self-tracking that 
reported on emotional burdens [15,42].

metadata.2: Proper Use of Quantification

__data__.text:
When players ascribed much authority to numbers and 
believed in numbers’ explanatory and prescriptive power, the power relation was produced and 
reproduced between people and technology.

metadata.2: Proper Use of Quantification

__data__.text:
But in this power relation, it is quantification tools 
that discipline and punish people, instead of people consciously manage technology use.

metadata.2: Proper Use of Quantification

__data__.text: In self-tracking the notion of self-knowledge was often traced back to Foucault to discuss how

metadata.2: Proper Use of Quantification

__data__.text: self-tracking technologies could help the production of self-knowledge [49,53].

metadata.2: Proper Use of Quantification

__data__.text:
However, 
Foucault stressed the importance of human agency in discovering self-knowledge, and examined 
how self-examination such as confession and reflective writing constituted technologies of the 
self [28].

metadata.2: Proper Use of Quantification

__data__.text:
That is, the discovery of self-knowledge is only enacted when people keep interrogating 
themselves about their relationships with any entities beyond the self, including the numbers.

metadata.2: Proper Use of Quantification

__data__.text:
However, when quantification tools acquired numerical authority from players, it became 
epistemologically dangerous if players blindly bestowed trust in quantification tools.

metadata.2: Proper Use of Quantification

__data__.text:
The 
numerical authority prescribed player actions towards caring about numbers, improving numbers, 
and judging others based on numbers.

metadata.2: Proper Use of Quantification

__data__.text: It is against this backdrop that certain players became aware of the ramifications of

metadata.2: Proper Use of Quantification

__data__.text: quantification.

metadata.2: Proper Use of Quantification

__data__.text: They stressed proper use of quantification.

metadata.2: Proper Use of Quantification

__data__.text:
By proper use we mean players 
individually developed normative judgments on how and when to use quantification tools.

metadata.2: Proper Use of Quantification

__data__.text:
They 
did not presume knowledge obtained from quantification was the absolute truth.

metadata.2: Proper Use of Quantification

__data__.text:
They perceived 
limitations of numbers and knew that they should use quantification in a proper way so as to 
avoid negative consequences such as frustration, anxiety, and aggression towards teammates.

metadata.2: Proper Use of Quantification

__data__.text:
Therefore, proper use of quantification in our study has two orientations: one towards the inner 
self where players took care of their own mind and emotion, and one towards the social where 
they tried to sort out the proper relationships with other players.

metadata.2: Proper Use of Quantification

__data__.text:
Both orientations were 
intertwined and together constituted proper use of quantification in players’ terms.

metadata.2: Proper Use of Quantification

__data__.text: The inward and outward orientations manifested themselves both cognitively and emotionally.

metadata.2: Proper Use of Quantification

__data__.text:
Along the inward orientation, cognitive proper use suggested that players could reasonably and 
logically develop understanding of their own skill and performance.

metadata.2: Proper Use of Quantification

__data__.text:
For example, a player would 
not make judgments about their skill based on bad KDA in one single match, but would perform 
detailed analysis to cultivate deeper understanding of themselves and the game, drawing from 
their situated knowledge.

metadata.2: Proper Use of Quantification

__data__.text:
Emotional proper use suggested that players could effectively manage 
their emotions when watching their own numbers.

metadata.2: Proper Use of Quantification

__data__.text:
They would easily cope with frustrations and 
anxiety.

metadata.2: Proper Use of Quantification

__data__.text: Along the outward orientation, cognitive proper use suggested that players could

__data__.text:
Emotional proper use suggested 
that players would not perform aggressive behaviors such as harassment towards their

metadata.2: Proper Use of Quantification

__data__.text: Importantly, what constituted proper use of quantification was highly individualistic.

For example, we have
